Remove check-dev-engines.

This was more trouble than it's worth. It wasn't actually catching
problematic situations.

This also fixes all remaining deprecation warnings!

Update test version of rusty-secrets to match prod

This is an unfortunate consequence of the current two-package.json
setup that used to be required by electron-builder. Apparently recent
versions are much smarter and do not require this setup. Would be great
to get away from and merge our two package.jsons to avoid this and
other complications.

Generates PNG-format icons for Linux builds

The electron-builder documentation states that we must use `icns2png` to
extract the macOS icon format into PNGs, for use in the Linux version of
the application. Added that command to the Ansible build logic, and also
updated the Makefile and gitignore file to recognize these files.
For Linux, build deb packages, not AppImage
Bump testing version of rusty-secrets.
Bump to 0.1.0.

Use Spectron for e2e tests

This is a minimal commit that replaces chromedriver and
selenium-webdriver with Spectron, and makes the changes necessary to get
the e2e tests passing using Spectron.

Most of the changes were necessitated by Spectron's use of WebdriverIO
instead of the old WebDriver API.

Remove old testing dependencies

chromedriver and selenium-webdriver have been replaced by Spectron. I
tested this by removing my `node_modules` directory, re-running `npm
install`, running `npm rebuild` due to an issue with rusty-secrets, then
confirming that both `npm run test` and `npm run test-e2e` succeed and
all tests pass.
bumped version of electron to address CVE-2018-10000006 (see https://electronjs.org/blog/protocol-handler-fix)

Upgrade electron-builder to fix building DMG on macOS

Fixes building DMGs, but breaks the app. Launching Sunder.app shows a
blank white window instead of the application's UI.

Convert to single package.json structure

Using a "two package.json structure" hasn't been necessary since
electron-builder version 8:
https://www.electron.build/tutorials/two-package-structure.

Fix macOS builds

Upgrading electron-builder somehow caused it to stop including the
output files from webpack in the final build. Adding the files
explicitly fixes it, and although there's a probably a more elegant
solution, I don't want to waste any more time on this.
rusty-secrets does not need to be in devDependencies

Use electron-mocha for unit tests

Since we switched to a single package.json we now only build our native
modules against Electron's version of Node. electron-mocha runs tests
using Electron as the Node runtime, which allows tests that require
native modules (e.g. `test/lib/crypto.spec.js`) to work.

I also had to change --compilers to --require because Mocha deprecated
--compilers [0], but electron-mocha jumped the gun and removed it
entirely [1].

[0]: https://github.com/mochajs/mocha/wiki/compilers-deprecation
[1]: https://github.com/jprichardson/electron-mocha/commit/ed12d6abebe91cd67cf371b6348a7bacb1666fa3

Remove now-unnecessary electron-rebuild

The new version of electron-builder we are using handles rebuilding
native dependencies in the post-install task, and specifically
recommends using `electron-builder install-app-deps` over
`electron-rebuild`.

Add required metadata for electron-builder

Fixes #98.

Updates email address in package.json

Switching to "sysadmin@" simply to avoid creating and maintaining an
email alias redirect. The operations team will receive messages there
and can pass to developers as necessary.

Updates git repo URL in package.json

We were still linking to the old "secretshare" repo title, since
deprecated in favor of the project name "Sunder". The old URL redirects
(thanks, GitHub!), but we should be listing the most accurate
information.

Declares correct license in package.json

Supplement to #89, in which a 3-Clause BSD license was added to the
project. We overlooked the `package.json` file, which also contains a
"license" field, and was erroneously set to "MIT". Updated to
"BSD-3-Clause", the format for which was determined by consulting:

  * https://docs.npmjs.com/files/package.json#license
  * https://spdx.org/licenses/

Should be all caught up now.

Update from moment 2.19.2

Moment is affected by CVE2017-18214 (DoS via crafted date string). Not only is it a dev dependency, sunder does not use this functionality and therefore shouldn't be affected. To avoid receiving and ignoring security notifications, version bump of concurrently is non-trivial and requires code changes. Overriding and bumping version of moment in `package.json` appears to be an easy fix.

Update `rusty-secrets` to v0.3.0

Note: rusty-secrets v0.3.0 now requires the Rust toolchain to be installed on the build machine.

Bumps electron 1.7.11 -> 1.8.6

Resolves two (2) CVEs:

  * CVE-2018-1000136
  * CVE-2018-1000118

neither of which pose a real problem for Sunder specifically, given the
network-less approach the app takes. Still, let's apply the available
patches as far as possible.

Upgrades hoek 4.2.0 -> 5.0.3

Addresses CVE-2018-3728. Does not appear to pose a problem for Sunder,
but applying the patch all the same to minimize security risk.

Note that a few other dependencies pulled in hoek v4.2.1, rather than
5.0.3, but 4.2.1 addresses CVE-2018-3728, as well.
Bumps version to 0.1.1

Update mocha to latest

Fixes a repo security warning about insecure version of growl.

Mocha depends on growl. Growl before 1.10.2 does not properly sanitize
input before passing it to exec, allowing for arbitrary command
execution (CVE-2017-16042).

This doesn't affect Sunder's security, since mocha is only used in
tests, but it's nice to be up to date and to remove the warning about
a vulnerable dependency from our github repo.

Update electron to 2.0.10

Fix npm run clean

The ./app directory no longer exists and the dist directory contains a
subdirectory structure that should be cleared out.

Update electron-builder and its dependencies

It's good to be up to date. Plus this happens to remove the dependency
on platform-specific 7zip-bin-* modules, which fixes the linux build
breakage accidentally incurred in 902ca4a.

Remove cryptiles dependency

A security vulnerability was found in cryptiles, a deeply nested
dependency in our package-lock.json. Updating spectron, fsevents, and
request modules to their latest versions effectively removes this
dependency.

Also worth noting is that these are all tools for development and test,
so Sunder should be unaffected by the vulnerability itself.
